# Task 1 - the code was initially written by ChatGPT
from plotnine import *

(ggplot(df1, 
    aes(
        x='income', 
        y='life_exp', 
        size='population', 
        color='four_regions'
    )) 
 + geom_text(aes(x=6000, y=50), label="2010", color="lightgrey", 
             size=250, alpha=0.07)
 + geom_point(alpha=0.6)  # Add transparency to bubbles
 + scale_x_continuous(trans='log2',
                      limits=(450, 80000),
                      breaks=[500, 1000, 2000, 4000, 8000, 16000, 32000, 64000],
                      labels=["500", "1k", "2k", "4k", "8k", "16k", "32k", "64k"])  # Log scale but with custom labels
 + scale_y_continuous(limits=(10,90), breaks=[20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90])
 + scale_size(range=(1, 30))  # Adjust size range for bubbles
 + scale_color_manual(values=["#1f77b4", "#2ca02c", "#d62728", "#ffdb0e"])  # Custom colors for regions
 + labs(x="Income", y="Life Expectancy")
 + guides(size=False) # removes size in legend
 + theme_minimal()
 + theme(figure_size=(10, 6))
)

import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *

# chatgpt helped edit this code to work
df1['income'] = pd.to_numeric(df1['income'], errors='coerce')

# removes null values
df1.dropna(subset=['income'], inplace=True)

# chatgpt created this code to create income categories
df1['income_category'] = pd.cut(df1['income'], 
                                 bins=[0, 500, 1000, 2000, 4000, 8000, 16000, 32000, 64000, float('inf')],
                                 labels=["<500", "500-1k", "1k-2k", "2k-4k", "4k-8k", "8k-16k", "16k-32k", "32k-64k", ">64k"])

(ggplot(df1, 
    aes(
        x='income_category',
        y='life_exp', 
        color='four_regions'
    ))
 #+ geom_text(aes(x=, y=50), label="2010", color="lightgrey", size=250, alpha=0.07) 
 + geom_boxplot(alpha=0.6)
 + scale_y_continuous(limits=(10,90), breaks=[20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90])
 + scale_color_manual(values=["#1f77b4", "#2ca02c", "#d62728", "#ffdb0e"])
 + labs(x="Income Categories", y="Life Expectancy")
 + theme_minimal()
 + theme(figure_size=(10, 6))
)

geom_boxplot in this particular instance is not a good way to represent the data opposed to geom_point. The visualization above is too cluttered as there are four box plots for each income category. Maybe this visualization would be better with less income categories but the visualization is still hard to understand at first glance. At a quick glance it is not as easy to tell which regions experience higher life expectancies at different income levels but if you look longer you may be able to. It is still not a clear enough visualization and does not represent a story as well as geom_point. In this case outliers are not as important to look at and understanding the IQR for each region at an income category is not necessary.

# Task 2
from plotnine import *

# provided by ChatGPT
def convert_energy(value):
    if isinstance(value, str) and 'K' in value:
        return float(value.replace('K', '')) * 1000
    return pd.to_numeric(value, errors='coerce') 

df2['energy'] = df2['energy'].apply(convert_energy)

# code structure reused from task 1 which was initially written by ChatGPT
(
    ggplot(df2, 
        aes(
            x='exports', 
            y='imports', 
            size='energy', 
            color='four_regions'
        )) 
    + geom_text(aes(x=110, y=250), label="1997", color="lightgrey", 
             size=250, alpha=0.07)
    + geom_point(alpha=0.6)  # Add transparency to bubbles
    + scale_x_continuous(limits=(1, 240),
                         breaks=[20, 40, 60, 80, 100, 120, 140, 160, 180, 200, 220],
                         labels=['20', '40', '60', '80', '100', '120', '140', '160', '180', '200', '220'])
    + scale_y_continuous(limits=(0, 450), breaks=[50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400])
    + scale_size(range=(1, 20))  # Adjust size range for bubbles
    + scale_color_manual(values=["#1f77b4", "#2ca02c", "#d62728", "#ffdb0e"])
    + labs(x="Exports (\% of GDP)", y="Imports (\% of GDP)")
    + guides(size=False) # removes size in legend
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(figure_size=(10, 6))
)

Below is a data visualization using geom_bin2d instead of geom_point to represent the same data.

from plotnine import *

(
    ggplot(df2, 
        aes(
            x='exports', 
            y='imports', 
            fill='four_regions'  # Fill by region
        )) 
    + geom_text(aes(x=110, y=250), label="1997", color="lightgrey", 
             size=250, alpha=0.07)
    + geom_bin2d(bins=30, alpha=0.7)  # Create a 2D histogram
    + scale_fill_manual(values=["#1f77b4", "#2ca02c", "#d62728", "#ffdb0e"])  # Custom colors for regions
    + scale_x_continuous(limits=(1, 240),
                         breaks=[20, 40, 60, 80, 100, 120, 140, 160, 180, 200, 220],
                         labels=['20', '40', '60', '80', '100', '120', '140', '160', '180', '200', '220'])
    + scale_y_continuous(limits=(0, 450), breaks=[50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400])
    + labs(x="Exports (\% of GDP)", y="Imports (\% of GDP)", fill="Region")
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(figure_size=(10, 6))
)

This visualization is a heatmap 2d histogram created by geom_bin2d. This visualization does show a similar graphic to what geom_point does. We can look at the darkness of each point to determine how many more points there are according to the region. It is an okay visualization however since you cannot tell exactly what colors are saturated more. It seems that from 20-40 on the x-axis Europe has less exports for more imports than other regions however compared to the visualization from geom_point we do not see the Americas represented at all. This could be due to the mixing of colors but this does make the visualization a little unclear or hard to interpret accurately.

Below is a data visualization using geom_line instead of geom_point to represent the same data.

# ChatGPT initially wrote this code
from plotnine import *

df3['gdp'] = pd.to_numeric(df3['gdp'], errors='coerce')

# Grouping by 'internet_users' and 'four_regions', calculating mean GDP and income
df3_summary = df3.groupby(['internet_users', 'four_regions']).agg({'gdp': 'mean', 'income': 'mean'}).reset_index()

(
    ggplot(df3_summary, 
        aes(
            x='internet_users', 
            y='gdp', 
            group='four_regions',
            color='four_regions',
            size='income'        
        )) 
    + geom_line(alpha=0.7) 
    + scale_x_continuous(limits=(0, 100),
                         breaks=[10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90],
                         labels=['10', '20', '30', '40', '50', '60', '70', '80', '90'])
    + scale_y_continuous(trans='log2',
                         limits=(100, 200000), 
                         breaks=[200, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, 10000, 20000, 50000, 100000],
                         labels=["200", "500", "1000", "2000", "5000", "10k", "20k", "50k", "100k"])
    + scale_color_manual(values=["#1f77b4", "#2ca02c", "#d62728", "#ffdb0e"])
    + scale_size(range=(1, 3))
    + labs(x="Individuals using the Internet", y="GDP/capita", color="Region", size="Average Income")
    + guides(size=False)
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(figure_size=(10, 6))
)

This visualization is a line chart created by geom_line. This visualization does show a similar graphic to what geom_point does. We can look at the thickness of each line to determine the size of income according to the region. This visualization represents the data semi-well. It shows us the GDP/capita according to each regions number of internet users and even represents income well enough. An issue with this visualization is it is difficult to distinguish the different lines and regions near 0 on the x-axis. However a benefit of using geom_line is that we can see trends clearly in how GDP/capita changes as internet users differ accross different regions.
